  "prompt": "Is Prime Minister of India a constitutional post?",
  "response": "Yes, the Prime Minister of India is a constitutional post. The position is established and defined in Part V, Chapter 1 of the Constitution of India, which deals with the executive branch of the government.\n\nKey points about the Prime Minister's constitutional role:\n\n1. According to Article 74 of the Constitution, there shall be a Prime Minister as the head of the Council of Ministers.\n\n2. The Prime Minister is appointed by the President of India and is usually the leader of the majority party or coalition in the Lok Sabha (Lower House of Parliament).\n\n3. The Prime Minister is the de facto head of the government and holds significant executive powers.\n\n4. The Prime Minister plays a crucial role in policy-making, selecting and leading the Council of Ministers, and advising the President.\n\n5. The constitutional provisions outline the Prime Minister's responsibilities, powers, and relationship with other constitutional bodies.\n\nSo, the Prime Minister is not just a political position but a constitutionally mandated role with specific powers and responsibilities defined in the Constitution of India.",
